434finalproj

Introduction

The goal of our final project is to predict the interest rate of a loan, based off various payment and income information. This dataset includes all loan data for all loans issued by Lending Club from 2007 to 2019, comprising over 2 million observations. Due to computing constraints, we have restricted our analysis to the first 5,000 observations. With this data, we will explore the regression methods we learned this quarter, as well as their sensitivity to the quality of training data.

Data Cleaning

Our dataset has many variables that caused instances of high linear dependance or other errors when designing our models, so we only kept variables that we though would be pertinent to our study.

Remove columns from dataset that have missing values in at least half the rows of the dataset. Also remove columns from data set where the values of each row are all the same.

loans <- Filter(function(x) length(unique(x))>1, loans)

Keep columns that we believe to be pertinent to interest rate and not linearly dependent. Also removed rows with N/A.

loans<-loans[ , which(names(loans) %in% c("funded_amnt", "term", "int_rate", "emp_length", "home_ownership", "annual_inc", "verification_status",  "purpose", "delinq_2yrs", "earliest_cr_line", "open_acc", "pub_rec", "revol_bal", "initial_list_status", "acc_open_past_24mths", "avg_cur_bal", "num_sats", "pub_rec_bankruptcies"))]

# turn date format into an int
dates = paste('01', loans$earliest_cr_line)
loans$earliest_cr_line = as.Date(dates, format = "%d %b-%Y")
loans$earliest_cr_line = as.integer(loans$earliest_cr_line)

# emp_length had some N/A stored as a string
loans = loans[!(loans$emp_length=="n/a"),]
loans$emp_length <- factor(loans$emp_length)
loans <- na.omit(loans)

Data Exploration

term vs.int_rate

ggplot(data=loans, aes(x=term, y=int_rate)) +
  geom_boxplot()

There seems to be a difference in average int_rate for the different term lengths. 60 month loans have an average higher interest rate.

funded amount vs.int_rate

ggplot(data=loans, aes(x=emp_length, y=int_rate)) +
  geom_boxplot()

There does not some to be any relationship between employment length and loan interest rate.

home_ownership vs.int_rate

ggplot(data=loans, aes(x=home_ownership, y=int_rate)) +
  geom_boxplot()

annual_inc vs.int_rate

ggplot(data=loans, aes(x=annual_inc, y=int_rate)) +
  geom_point()

From this graph, there seems to be a slight trend where higher income people get lower interest rates.

plot(loans[,c(1,3,6, 9,10)])

plot(loans[,c(3,11, 15:17)])

for (col in c(1,3,6, 9:11, 15:17)){
  hist(loans[,col], main = names(loans[col]))

From the matrix of plots we can see that int_rate does not seem to have a non-linear relationship with any variable other that annual_inc.

Variable Selection

For variable selection, we tested four different methods, Forwards stepwise, Backwards stepwise, Ridge regression, and LASSO. For Ridge regression and LASSO, we used cross validation in order to find the best value of \(\lambda\).

set.seed(2)
train = sample(nrow(loans), nrow(loans)/2)
loans_train<-loans[train,]
loans_test<-loans[-train,]

Forward stepwise

predict.regsubsets =function (object ,newdata ,id ,...){
form=as.formula (object$call [[2]])
mat=model.matrix (form ,newdata )
coefi =coef(object ,id=id)
xvars =names (coefi )
mat[,xvars ]%*% coefi
}

forwardm <- regsubsets(int_rate~., data = loans_train, method = "forward", nvmax = ncol(loans)-1)
## Warning in leaps.setup(x, y, wt = wt, nbest = nbest, nvmax = nvmax, force.in =
## force.in, : 1 linear dependencies found
val.errors <- rep(NA, ncol(loans)-1)
for (i in 1:(ncol(loans)-1)) {
    pred <- predict.regsubsets(forwardm, loans_test, i)
    val.errors[i] <- mean((loans_test$int_rate - pred)^2)
}
min(val.errors)
## [1] 19.46113

Backward stepwise

backwardm <- regsubsets(int_rate~., data = loans_train, method = "backward", nvmax = ncol(loans)-1)
## Warning in leaps.setup(x, y, wt = wt, nbest = nbest, nvmax = nvmax, force.in =
## force.in, : 1 linear dependencies found
val.errors <- rep(NA, ncol(loans)-1)
for (i in 1:(ncol(loans)-1)) {
    pred <- predict.regsubsets(backwardm, loans_test, i)
    val.errors[i] <- mean((loans_test$int_rate - pred)^2)
}

min(val.errors)
## [1] 19.53017

Ridge Regression

library(glmnet)

x <- model.matrix(int_rate ~ ., loans)[,-1]
y <- loans$int_rate

cv.out <- cv.glmnet(x[train,], y[train], alpha = 0)
bestlam <- cv.out$lambda.min
ridgem <- glmnet(x[train,],y[train],alpha =0, lambda =bestlam)
ridge.pred <- predict(ridgem, s = bestlam, newx = x[-train,])
mean((y[-train] - ridge.pred)^2)
## [1] 19.50978

LASSO

cv.out <- cv.glmnet(x[train,], y[train], alpha = 1)
bestlam <- cv.out$lambda.min
lassom <- glmnet(x[train,],y[train],alpha =1, lambda =bestlam)
lasso.pred <- predict(lassom, s = bestlam, newx = x[-train,])
mean((y[-train] - lasso.pred)^2)
## [1] 19.50922

Forward Stepwise ended up returning the lowest test error at about 19.46 followed by LASSO and Ridge Regression at 19.51 and the stepwise backwards at 19.53. All methods return very similar test errors, so using any method should probably be acceptable. For our own varaible reduction method, we are going to use the forwards subset selection because it returned the best test error.

Polynomial Regression

  glm.fit = glm(data = loans, int_rate~poly(funded_amnt, poly_degrees[i])+ poly(annual_inc,poly_degrees[i])+poly(delinq_2yrs, poly_degrees[i]) + poly(earliest_cr_line, poly_degrees[i])+ poly(revol_bal, poly_degrees[i])+ poly(acc_open_past_24mths, poly_degrees[i])+poly(num_sats, poly_degrees[i]) + term + home_ownership + verification_status+purpose+initial_list_status)

For the polynomial models, there were drastic changes in test error as the size of the training data changed. While the model with the most training error performed at a similar error rate to previous models, both the smaller models had very larger training errors, and likely would perfom better for a lower polynomial degree.

GAM

We can fit a general additive model using splines to our model Since we determined that only annual_inc may have a non-linear relation ship with int_rate, we can fit it with a smoothing spline and add it to our model

Boosting

For boosting, we must determine the optimal tuning parameter lambda through cross validation.

Boosting n = 500

set.seed(1)
lambda.seq <- c(seq(from = .01, to = .1, by = .01), seq(from = .1, to = 1, by = .05))
test.errs <- numeric(length(lambda.seq))

for (i in 1:length(lambda.seq)) {
    boost.interest <- gbm(int_rate~., data = loans_trainsm, distribution = "gaussian",
                         n.trees = 1000, shrinkage = lambda.seq[i])
    yhat.boost <- predict(boost.interest, newdata = loans_testsm, n.trees = 1000)
    test.errs[i] <- mean((yhat.boost - loans_testsm$int_rate)^2)
}
plot(lambda.seq, test.errs, type = "b")

tab_matrix = matrix(nrow = 3, ncol = 2)
colnames(tab_matrix) = c("lambda", "test error")
rownames(tab_matrix) = c("training n=500", "training n=1000", "training n=4591")
tab_matrix[1,1] = lambda.seq[which.min(test.errs)]
tab_matrix[1,2] = min(test.errs)

lambda.seq[which.min(test.errs)]
## [1] 0.02
min(test.errs)
## [1] 20.05818

For the small training set, the best lambda is 0.02 and it has a test error of 20.06.

Neural Networks n = 500

set.seed(1)

                   linout = TRUE, trace = FALSE)

KNN and Principal Components Regression

We wanted to include a note on these two models, as they were among the ones we considered for analysis. As are possible with categorical variables, and we had multiple variables with many categorical levels, we determined KNN and PC Regression were not suitable models for our dataset.

Conclusion

With all of our models, we had a range of test errors from to 18.7 to over 250. Overall, the random forests and boosting models performed the best across the three sizes of our training data. The models with less training data tended to have higher test errors, and were especially high when using models with large variance, such as polynomials. Models with higher interpretability and a more visual form, such as regular trees and neural networks had test error rates of around 10-20% higher than more standard models, but are likely easier to explain. While the largest training data generally lead to the best test results, there was no clear pattern between the small and medium models. Overall, the varying results in this project for different models, tuning parameters, and training data sizes show the importance of trying multiple approaches to analysis in order to have comprehensive analysis.
